# Loose Pear Diamonds: Natural & Lab Grown Prices at Blue Nile {{year}}

Loose pear diamonds at Blue Nile start at $3,803 for a GIA-certified natural 1ct D-VS1 Ideal cut stone and $1,006 for an IGI-certified lab grown 1ct D-VVS1 Ideal — both available to purchase as a loose pear diamond stone, separate from any ring setting. This guide covers every tier of loose pear diamonds for sale at Blue Nile: natural GIA stones from 1ct through 4ct+, lab grown IGI and GIA stones from 1ct through 4.5ct+, certification standards, the buying sequence, and the framework for selecting a loose pear cut diamond before committing to a setting.

Buying loose pear diamonds is the correct approach for buyers who want to optimize the stone independently of the setting — choosing the best pear diamond stone their budget allows and then selecting or custom-ordering a setting that fits it. Every dollar spent on a setting is a dollar not spent on the stone. The loose buying model prioritizes stone quality first.

## TL;DR: Loose Pear Diamonds — What to Know Before You Buy

- **Natural loose pear diamonds** at Blue Nile (GIA certified, Ideal cut): 1ct from [$3,803](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29112328?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational); 2ct from [$22,605](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28996100?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational); 3ct from [$45,539](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28435605?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational); 4ct from [$75,775](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/26211394?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational).
- **Lab grown loose pear diamonds** at Blue Nile (IGI certified, Ideal/Excellent cut): 1ct from [$1,006](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/26932733?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational); 2ct from [$2,692](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/27379422?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational); 3ct from [$5,316](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28628628?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational); 4ct from [$7,505](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/27310622?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational).
- **Only buy GIA or IGI certified.** An uncertified loose pear diamond stone is unverifiable. The $150–$300 certificate cost is not a savings opportunity — it is the only independent verification that the stone is what the seller claims.
- **Stone first, setting second.** Allocate 70–80% of your total ring budget to the loose pear diamond stone. → Pick the best stone your budget allows, then choose the setting from what remains. Doing it in reverse — falling in love with a setting and fitting the stone into leftover budget — is the single most common mistake in loose diamond buying.
- **Priority:** [GIA 1ct D-VS1 Ideal at $3,803](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29112328?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) for natural; [IGI 1ct D-VVS1 Ideal lab at $1,006](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/26932733?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) for lab grown. These are the price anchors. Every other loose pear diamond purchase should be evaluated relative to these entry points.

## What Are Loose Pear Diamonds and Where to Buy Them

A loose pear diamond is a pear brilliant cut diamond that has been cut, polished, graded, and certificated — but not yet set into a ring, pendant, earring, or other piece of jewelry. Purchasing a loose pear diamond stone separately from a setting allows the buyer to make two independent decisions: which diamond to buy, and which setting to put it in. These decisions do not have to happen simultaneously, and separating them typically produces a better outcome for both. For a complete overview of how pear diamonds are graded, cut, and evaluated before purchase, see the [Pear Cut Diamond Guide](/pear-cut-diamond).

**Where to buy loose pear diamonds:**
Blue Nile is the largest online retailer of loose pear diamonds for sale, with inventory spanning natural GIA-certified pear diamonds and lab grown IGI, GIA, and GCAL-certified pear diamonds across every carat weight and grade combination. Every loose pear diamond on Blue Nile includes a gemological certificate, high-resolution photography, a 360° video, and detailed specification data (measurements, depth %, table %, symmetry grade, polish grade, fluorescence, and girdle characteristics).

Blue Nile also provides a setting service: after purchasing a loose pear diamond stone, you can add a ring setting from Blue Nile's inventory and they will mount the stone before shipping. This is the most common use of Blue Nile's loose diamond model — buy the stone at the best available price and grade, then select from hundreds of pear-compatible ring settings at Blue Nile or from any local jeweler who accepts customer-supplied stones.

**Who buys loose pear shaped diamonds:**
- Engagement ring buyers who want to choose the stone and setting independently
- Buyers upgrading an existing ring setting with a new stone
- Custom jewelry buyers who have commissioned a setting from a local jeweler
- Collectors and investors purchasing natural pear diamonds as assets
- Buyers who want lab grown loose pear diamonds for pendants or earrings where setting choices are limited

## The Certification Trap

The phrase "loose pear diamonds wholesale" appears frequently in searches because buyers are looking for loose pear diamonds at prices below standard retail. What these searches surface — wholesale marketplaces, uncertified stone sellers, and discounted diamond brokers — is often a poor-value alternative to certified retail, not a better one.

The Certification Trap is the false economy of purchasing a loose pear diamond stone without a GIA or IGI certificate. The trap works like this: an uncertified seller offers a 1ct pear diamond for $2,800 — below the Blue Nile GIA-certified entry price of $3,803. The buyer saves $1,003 on the stone price. What the buyer cannot verify without an independent certificate: that the stone is actually 1.00ct and not 0.92ct; that the color grade is D-VS1 and not G-SI2; that there is no fracture fill or clarity enhancement that will affect long-term durability; and that the stone is a natural diamond and not a simulant.

Gemological certificates from GIA or IGI are the only independent documentation of what a loose pear diamond stone actually is. GIA and IGI are not affiliated with the retailer selling the stone. Their grading reports are issued based on physical examination of the stone in their laboratory, not based on the seller's description. An uncertified loose pear diamond is only as accurately described as the seller's willingness to be honest about it.

**The actual cost of the Certification Trap:**
A retail GIA certificate for a 1ct pear diamond costs approximately $100–$150 when purchased separately from a diamond grader. If a seller is offering a loose pear diamond "without a certificate to save you money," the actual savings on the certificate is $100–$150 — not the $1,000+ discount that appears in the advertised price. The price difference between a certified and uncertified stone of the same nominal grade is significantly larger than the certificate cost, meaning the uncertified stone is either a lower grade than claimed, or smaller than claimed, or carries some other deficiency that would appear on an independent certificate.

The correct approach: buy only GIA or IGI certified loose pear diamonds from reputable retailers. Blue Nile includes the GIA or IGI certificate with every loose diamond purchase at no additional charge. The certificate is built into the stone price, not an add-on.

![The Certification Trap: Why Uncertified Pear Diamonds Cost More — uncertified $2,800 vs GIA certified $3,803 with full grade verification](/images/bn-pear-loose-2.avif)

**IGI vs GIA for loose pear diamonds:**
Both IGI and GIA certify loose pear diamonds. GIA is more widely recognized globally and commands a name-recognition premium — at 1ct, GIA and IGI D-VVS1 pear diamonds are available at the same price point on Blue Nile, making GIA the default choice at this grade tier. At higher carats and clarity grades (D-IF at 2ct+), GIA commands a meaningful premium: a GIA 2ct D-IF pear lab is $6,393 vs IGI 2ct D-IF at $4,941. For most buyers, IGI at D-VVS1 Ideal is the optimal lab grown pear certification choice; GIA is the standard for natural pear diamonds at every tier.

