![Loose Pear Diamond: Natural GIA vs Lab Grown IGI price by carat — 1ct to 4ct savings from 84% to 90%](/images/bn-pear-loose-1.avif)

The savings increase with carat weight because natural pear diamond prices scale super-linearly with carat (see [The Carat Jump Tax](/pear-diamond-size-chart)) while lab grown prices scale proportionally. For buyers whose priority is stone size, the lab grown loose pear diamond produces a larger stone at every budget tier compared to natural. For buyers who specifically want a natural origin stone — for geological authenticity, resale considerations, or personal preference — the natural GIA price is the accurate market price.

**Resale consideration:** Lab grown diamonds carry lower resale values than natural diamonds. A loose natural pear diamond stone purchased today retains value more predictably than a lab grown stone. If resale or heirloom value matters, natural is the correct choice. If wearing enjoyment and stone size matter more, lab grown is the correct choice.

## What to Check Before Buying Any Loose Pear Diamond Stone

Buying a loose pear cut diamond requires the same proportions evaluation as any pear diamond, plus certification verification. The complete checklist:

**Certificate:** GIA or IGI only. Verify the certificate number on the GIA Report Check or IGI Report Check before completing any purchase. The certificate number is printed on the stone's girdle by laser inscription; it matches the number on the grading report.

**Measurements:** Check the listed mm dimensions. Calculate L/W ratio (Length ÷ Width). For an elongated pear diamond, target 1.60–1.65:1. For a classic pear, target 1.50–1.60:1. For an east-west setting, target 1.40–1.55:1.

**Depth %:** 58–64% is the ideal range. Eliminate stones outside this range without exception.

**Table %:** 53–65% is the target range. Avoid extremes in either direction.

**Symmetry:** GIA Excellent or Very Good minimum. Below Very Good shows visible asymmetry.

**Polish:** GIA Excellent or Very Good minimum.

**Video:** Watch the 360° video on every stone's Blue Nile detail page. Evaluate bow-tie severity. A faint shadow at the center is acceptable; a solid dark band is not. No still photograph reveals the bow-tie — only video does.

**Shoulder curvature:** View the outline photograph at the largest available size. Both shoulder arcs (from widest point to wing tips) must be smooth, continuous curves with no flat spots or pinch points.

**Fluorescence:** Blue fluorescence in natural pear diamonds is not always negative — in D-F color stones, strong fluorescence can make the stone appear slightly hazy under UV light sources. For natural pear diamonds above $5,000, check the fluorescence field on the certificate. None or Faint fluorescence is the conservative choice.

