## Final Verdict: Which Loose Pear Diamond to Buy

**Best natural loose pear diamond stone under $5,000:** [GIA 1ct D-VS1 Ideal at $3,803](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29112328?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational). D colorless, VS1 clarity, Ideal cut, GIA certified. This is the correct stone for buyers who want natural origin, top-tier documentation, and a complete ring under $5,000. No natural loose pear diamond stone available today delivers more per dollar at 1ct.

**Best lab grown loose pear diamond stone at 1ct:** [IGI 1ct D-VVS1 Ideal at $1,006](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/26932733?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational). Or spend $542 more for [IGI 1ct D-IF Ideal at $1,548](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/27731891?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) — Internally Flawless is the upgrade recommendation because the price gap between VVS1 and IF is smaller in lab grown than in natural.

**Best overall loose pear diamond purchase:** [GIA 2ct D-VVS1 Ideal lab pear at $2,692](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28761071?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational). Two carats, D color, VVS1 clarity, Ideal cut, GIA certified, $2,692. The natural equivalent starts at $22,605. A complete ring with this stone and a quality setting totals $3,300–$4,000. No loose pear diamond stone at any price or origin produces a more compelling total value.

**Best natural pear diamond stone above 1ct:** [GIA 2ct E-VVS1 Ideal at $22,605](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28996100?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational). For buyers committed to natural origin at 2ct, this is the only entry-point option in current Blue Nile inventory. Rare, extraordinary, and correctly priced at market.

## Expert Summary

> Buyers searching for loose pear diamonds are often doing something right — separating the stone decision from the setting decision is exactly correct. The mistake I see is the sequence getting reversed anyway: a buyer researches the stone, falls in love with a setting they saw on Instagram, budgets for both together, and ends up compromising the stone to afford the setting. The Stone-First Rule is not complicated — allocate 70–80% of your total budget to the diamond, then pick the setting from what's left. The setting can be upgraded in five years. The stone cannot, without starting over. The other thing worth saying about loose pear diamonds for sale online: the certification check is not optional. GIA certificate numbers are verifiable in 30 seconds on gia.edu. IGI certificate numbers are verifiable on igiworldwide.com. Do this before any purchase. If a seller cannot provide a verifiable certificate number, the stone is not worth the price being asked.
>
> — Farzana Hasan, Fine Jewelry Analyst

## Frequently Asked Questions

### Where can I buy loose pear diamonds?

Blue Nile is the largest retailer of certified loose pear diamonds online, with inventory of GIA-certified natural pear diamonds and IGI, GIA, and GCAL-certified lab grown pear diamonds at every carat weight and grade tier. All stones come with the original grading certificate, photography, 360° video, and complete specification data. Blue Nile also mounts the loose stone into a setting of your choice before shipping.

### What is the cheapest loose pear diamond?

The cheapest GIA-certified natural loose pear diamond at Blue Nile starts at $3,803 for a 1ct D-VS1 Ideal cut stone. The cheapest IGI-certified lab grown loose pear diamond starts at $1,006 for a 1ct D-VVS1 Ideal cut stone. Sub-1ct natural pear diamonds are available at lower price points (approximately $900–$2,200 at the 0.50ct tier) — filter Blue Nile's [pear diamond inventory](https://www.bluenile.com/diamonds/pear-shaped?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) by carat range to see current sub-1ct options.

### What does a loose pear diamond stone cost?

Natural GIA loose pear diamond stones at Blue Nile: 1ct $3,803–$8,272+; 2ct $22,605–$27,700+; 3ct $45,539–$109,207+; 4ct $75,775–$124,452+. Lab grown IGI loose pear diamond stones: 1ct $1,006–$1,548; 2ct $2,692–$6,393; 3ct $5,316–$9,636; 4ct $7,505–$17,598.

### Are loose pear diamonds cheaper wholesale?

Individual consumers do not have access to true wholesale loose pear diamond pricing, which is reserved for licensed dealers and manufacturers purchasing in bulk. "Wholesale" pricing offered to consumers typically indicates uncertified stones, overstated original prices, or lower grades than represented. GIA and IGI certified loose pear diamonds at Blue Nile represent current competitive retail market pricing — not inflated MSRP.

### Should I buy a GIA or IGI certified loose pear diamond?

Both GIA and IGI certifications are legitimate for loose pear diamonds. GIA is more widely recognized globally and is the standard for natural pear diamonds. For lab grown loose pear diamonds, IGI at D-VVS1 Ideal is typically the best value — at 1ct, GIA and IGI lab pear diamonds are available at the same price ($1,073), making GIA the tie-breaker choice when prices match. At higher clarity tiers (D-IF, D-FL), GIA commands a premium over IGI: $1,452 more at 2ct D-IF ($6,393 GIA vs $4,941 IGI).

### What is the difference between a loose pear diamond and a pear diamond stone?

No difference. "Loose pear diamond," "pear diamond stone," "pear loose diamond," "pear shaped diamond stone," and "pear cut loose diamond" all describe the same product: a pear brilliant cut diamond that has been graded and certificated but not yet mounted in a setting. All these terms are searchable on Blue Nile under the pear diamond filter.

### Can I bring my own loose pear diamond to a jeweler?

Yes. A loose pear diamond stone purchased at Blue Nile can be taken to any jeweler for setting in a custom or standard ring. Blue Nile also offers their own setting service — add a pear-compatible setting to your cart alongside the loose stone and they will mount it before shipping. Local jewelers routinely accept customer-supplied loose diamonds; request a quote before committing to a setting choice.

### How do I know if a loose pear diamond is real?

A GIA or IGI certificate number is the primary verification method. Every certified loose pear diamond has a laser inscription on the girdle with the certificate number. Verify the number at gia.edu (for GIA) or igiworldwide.com (for IGI). The certificate confirms the stone's identity, measurements, and grade combination. An uncertified "loose pear diamond" cannot be independently verified and should not be purchased at anything approaching certified market prices.

### What carat loose pear diamond is best for an engagement ring?

The 1ct loose pear diamond is the most popular engagement ring choice — it measures approximately 8.5×5.7mm at standard L/W ratios and provides a clearly visible center stone in any solitaire or halo setting. For buyers who want a bold statement, the 2ct lab grown loose pear diamond at $2,692 is the single most compelling value in this category: 10.5×7.0mm face-up, D-VVS1 GIA certified, for a total ring under $3,500.

### What is the best loose pear diamond for a pendant?

For a pendant, a loose pear diamond at 0.50ct–1ct is the most practical range. The stone hangs vertically, so the elongated silhouette of the pear creates a natural drop effect. A [1ct GIA D-VS1 natural pear at $3,803](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29112328?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) is the natural recommendation; a [1ct IGI D-VVS1 lab pear at $1,006](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/26932733?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) is the lab alternative at 74% less.

### What L/W ratio should a loose pear diamond have?

For an engagement ring solitaire: 1.55–1.65:1. For an elongated pear diamond ring: 1.60–1.70:1. For a pendant or drop: 1.45–1.75:1. For an east-west ring: 1.40–1.55:1. Calculate the ratio from the listed mm measurements on Blue Nile's detail page: Length ÷ Width. See the [Pear Diamond Ideal Proportions Guide](/pear-diamond-ideal-proportions) for the full 8-step evaluation framework.

### What is the best color for a loose pear shaped diamond stone?

D through F color is the recommendation for loose pear diamonds in white gold or platinum settings — the pear's elongated facets make color concentration at the pointed tip more visible than in round brilliants. I color is the practical minimum for white metal settings. In yellow gold or rose gold, G through J color is acceptable; the metal's warmth masks any stone warmth. For lab grown loose pear diamonds, defaulting to D or E color is rational since the price difference is minimal: $1,006 (D) vs $1,038 (E) at 1ct IGI D/E-VVS1.

